rl":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/labels/rationals","name":"rationals","color":"fbca04","default":false,"description":"The Rational type and values thereof"},{"id":171885699,"node_id":"MDU6TGFiZWwxNzE4ODU2OTk=","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/labels/maths","name":"maths","color":"009800","default":false,"description":"Mathematical functions"}],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":44,"created_at":"2015-06-01T15:30:36Z","updated_at":"2023-07-17T02:45:31Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"MEMBER","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"Over in https://github.com/tlycken/Interpolations.jl/pull/36#issuecomment-106895591 and https://github.com/tlycken/Interpolations.jl/pull/37 it was discovered that doing computations with `Rational` is slow, because basically every usage calls `gcd` and `div`. The advantage of calling `gcd` and `div` is that it makes the type much less vulnerable to overflow, and that is a Good Thing. But as we discovered, certain computations may not need that kind of care, so there may be room for a faster variant. Switching to a [stripped down variant](https://github.com/tlycken/Interpolations.jl/blob/0255ad884b4684da42f5f01db372e642844c1bae/src/ratio.jl) provided an approximate 50-fold speed boost. 

I suspect certain computations may demand an implementation that is as minimalistic as that `Ratio` type. There may also be an area of intermediate interest, where a `Rational`-like object is represented in terms of pre-factorized numbers, perhaps numerator and denominator each being a `Dict{Int,Int}` representing the base and power of the factors.
